*Introducing Partner Fulfillment MIS Report*


As billing complexity increases, so does the need for precise, auditable
data, especially when multiple fulfilment partners and execution paths are
involved.


With this release, we=E2=80=99re introducing a new* Fulfillment MIS report*=
 that
provides a clean, order-level view of all billable fulfilment transactions
executed by partners.


This report is designed to give finance and operations teams a clearer,
more reliable foundation for reconciliation, audits, and downstream billing
workflows.
Why We Built This

The existing transactions download offered a single, default report that
mixed different transaction contexts and made it harder to isolate
fulfilment-level charges, particularly when orders moved across partners or
were partially cancelled.

This led to:

   -

   Difficulty reconciling partner invoices
   -

   Noise from zero-value or irrelevant entries
   -

   Limited visibility into fulfilment-specific charges


The new MIS report addresses this by focusing only on *non-zero,
order-level fulfilment transactions specific to each partner request* =E2=
=80=94
nothing more, nothing less.
What=E2=80=99s New


A Dedicated MIS Report

When downloading transactions from the *Billing* page, you now have the
option to select *Partner Fulfilment* instead of the default download.

This report:

   -

   Contains *only non-zero entries*
   -

   Includes *only orders fulfilled by partners (3PL/PPN)*
   -

   Is generated at an *order fulfilment level*, not a generic transaction
   level

How Entries Are Created

The report reflects *each fulfilment request created*, not just each order.

For example:

   -

   If 100 orders are completed in a day and *60 are fulfilled by partners*,
   the report will contain *entries for 60 orders *(can be more basis
   number of fulfillment per order)
   -

   Orders fulfilled by captive riders are excluded
   -

   If an order is first booked with one partner, cancelled with a charge,
   and then re-booked with another partner, *each fulfilment attempt
   appears as a separate entry*


This ensures every billable interaction with a partner is captured
accurately.
What This Means For You

You now get a report that reflects *exactly what needs to be billed or
reconciled*.

This means:

   -

   Cleaner billing data with no zero-value clutter
   -

   Accurate visibility into partner fulfilment charges
   -

   Easier reconciliation when orders involve cancellations or re-bookings
   -

   A report structure that aligns directly with finance workflows


Whether you=E2=80=99re reviewing daily execution or closing monthly books, =
the data
is now easier to trust and easier to use.
What=E2=80=99s Next

We=E2=80=99re continuing to strengthen reporting and financial transparency=
, making
it easier to move from execution data to billing-ready insights.

Expect deeper control, richer breakdowns, and smarter reporting flows ahead=
.
